Causal Inference for Computational Social Science

Author

Christy Hsu

Published

July 31, 2025

Abstract

July 15th

In his 1997 article, Mark Tessler used 1988 survey data to argue that understanding popular support for Islamist movements in Arab countries requires distinguishing between Islam as personal and societal salience and the âPolitical Islamâ. This distinction can lead us to see that attitudes toward personal and societal Islam do not necessarily align with attitudes toward political Islam. This insight challenged the prevailing assumption at the time, that support for Islamists, especially their anti-Western attitudes and actions in the news, stemmed directly from religious motives and thus an inevitable âclash of civilizationsâ owing to contradictory value systems. Thus, exempted attention to the socioeconomic and political grievances that has even stronger associations with the popular leaning to Islamic movements. This project hopes to begin by demonstrating how misleading impressions about political Islam may come about. An initial attempt looked to when simply equating personal religiosity with support for extending religion into the political sphere. Applying concerns from causal inference, with the 1988 survey data at hand, a preliminary analysis started by the relationship between support for political Islam, religiosity, and anti-Western attitudes. By grouping respondents by higher and lower levels of support for Islamists can induce the association of religiosity and anti-West sentiment.

Dataset Overview and Identified Limitations

1988 Jamal al-Suwaidi Survey Data

This survey was carried out in mid-1988, with samples drawn from Cairo and Kuwait, targeting the urban Sunni adults: Egyptians (n = 292), Kuwaitis (n = 300) and Palestinians residing in Kuwait (n = 293).1

from the writings of key thinkers (in progress)

In the third quarter of the 19th century, people looked to Islam for a solution in order to deal with the encounter of the decentralized and diverse Ottoman empire to the unified and militant western modern nation states. One case we can look to is Jamal al-Din al-Afghani. In his writing âPlan for Islamic Unityâ in 1884, al-Afghani advocated for the Islam states to reunite as he treated Islam as a civilization, he anticipated that once this unity of Muslims established, they will gain enough strength to counter the European imperialism that was at the time taking an interest in the Muslim world. Therefore, this approach to Islam was an instrumental and political one, much because of a sense of existential threat that Muslims might no longer be able to rule themselves. It is worth noting that, al-Afghaniâs calling for modernizing Islam and for unifying the Muslims, that call implies that âIslamâ, the Muslims and the Islamic community at the late 19th century were all on the far side of being unified. The diversity in the Ottoman Empire and in the religion itself was the reality of the late 19th century. We can see that in the view of al-Afghani, their immediate problem was about the community of this world, thus, he borrowed concepts from the west trying to foment a unity in the sense, he supported the military reform. His attitude can also be observed in his cooperation with Ottoman Sultan Abdulhamid II in promoting pan-Islamism, expecting to add on to the integrity and the strength of the Ottoman Empire. Al-afghaniâs Islam revival has much to do with societal and political problems rather than the religion itself. The ultimate goal of this movement or of pan-Islamism was to reclaim strength for the Muslim world. This aligns with the 19th century modernizing reforms carried out by the Ottoman Sultan, but also a reflection on why modernizing and westernizing was taking place but the empire was still disintegrating.
